Andrew Ross Sorkin has been a longtime
friend=E2=80=94his mother-in-law lives in my building, he and his family li=
ve around the corner, and I=E2=80=99ve contributed a piece here and there (=
 https://www.nytimes.com/2025/02/22/business/dealbook/elon-musk-jack-welch-=
cuts.html?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_con=
tent=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action=
&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) to DealBook over =
the years. I have always marveled at his tireless ability to do it all: bof=
fo New York Times Wall Street reporter turned columnist; founder of DealBoo=
k; amazing master of ceremonies and
executive producer for its annual conference, Wall Street=E2=80=99s Davos, =
that never fails to make headlines; and anchor of CNBC=E2=80=99s Squawk Box=
=2E Plus, Andrew was one of the creator=
s of Billions on Showtime, which ran f=
or seven remarkable seasons; and, of course, the author of the bestselling =
blockbuster Too Big to Fail, the inside account of the 2008 financial crisi=
s, which was turned into an HBO movie. Is there any other journalist alive =
collecting checks from The New York
Times Co., Paramount Global, and Comcast at the same time?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

As soon as news emerged about Andrew=E2=80=99s forthcoming book on the Grea=
t Depression, titled 1929: The Inside Story of the Greatest Crash in Wall S=
treet History, I was eager to chat about the project and how it came togeth=
er. I first caught wind of the book back in December 2023, but Andrew wasn=
=E2=80=99t ready to spill the beans. At that point
it was still an amorphous work in progress, and he=E2=80=99s too much of a =
pro to discuss a project prematurely.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Like many of us, Andrew had a vague sense of what occurred during the 1929 =
crash. He=E2=80=99d read the classics=E2=80=94among them, John Kenneth Galb=
raith=E2=80=99s The Great Crash and John Brooks=E2=80=99 Once in Golconda. =
But on a vacation seven or eight years ago, he
decided to get more serious, downloading a bunch of books on the subject. M=
ost of them, he said, had an =E2=80=9Carmchair=E2=80=9D quality: they were =
distant, a tad dry, lacking a crisp, flowing narrative or any feeling that =
the reader was present while events were unfolding. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=
=99t feel like I had read a true character-driven, narrative ticktock, in-t=
he-room, fly-on-the-wall kind of thing,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CI was=
 a little surprised. I thought, Maybe someone has written it. But wouldn=E2=
=80=99t it be really fun
to try to figure out if I could do that?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Andrew set out to see if he could re-create that inside-the-room feel for t=
he incredible events of 1929. Unlike the 2008 financial crisis, which was p=
laying out before his eyes in real time, the major players from the Depress=
ion were long dead. (This comes with its perks, too, as any author knows=E2=
=80=A6) There were plenty of academics to talk to, of course, but he was lo=
oking for
the original source material of the people involved=E2=80=94letters, diary =
entries, memoirs=E2=80=94the stuff tucked away in obscure archives across t=
he country. At times, he doubted if he could find what he needed=E2=80=94th=
e normal authorial anxiety. Unsure of whether he could produce the narrativ=
e he wanted, he didn=E2=80=99t even initially sell the book to his publishe=
r. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t know whether I=E2=80=99d be able to get the so=
rt of granular detail that I was looking for,=E2=80=9D he told me.

