;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Andrew Ross Sorkin</strong> has be=
en a longtime
friend=E2=80=94his mother-in-law lives in my building, he and his family li=
ve around the corner, and I=E2=80=99ve contributed a piece here and <a href=
=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0d=
WTlNWNW80MnRDNG9kRjB1andITT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMj=
AyNS8wMi8yMi9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9lbG9uLW11c2stamFjay13ZWxjaC1jdXRzLmh0b=
Ww_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPURyeStQb3dkZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgyJTJGMjMlMkYyNSUy=
OVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PURyeStQb3dkZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgyJTJGMTYlMkY=
yNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b2=
1lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjN=
jA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjA5MzUyNn0/0577e9d45333ec409cc7d87d438d=
ba2fbc73c3527390d38ba19ff96f03f17f3e" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;co=
lor:#d40000;">there</a> to DealBook over the years. I have always marveled =
at his tireless ability to do it all: boffo <em>New York Times</em> Wall St=
reet reporter turned columnist; founder of DealBook; amazing master of cere=
monies and
executive producer for its annual conference, Wall Street=E2=80=99s Davos, =
that never fails to make headlines; and anchor of CNBC=E2=80=99s <em>Squawk=
 Box</em>. Plus, Andrew was one of the creators of <em>Billions</em> on Sho=
wtime, which ran for seven remarkable seasons; and, of course, the author o=
f the bestselling blockbuster <em>Too Big to Fail</em>, the inside account =
of the 2008 financial crisis, which was turned into an HBO movie. Is there =
any other journalist alive collecting checks from The New York
Times Co., Paramount Global, and Comcast at the same time?=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">As soon as news emerged about Andrew=E2=80=99s forthcoming book o=
n the Great Depression, titled <em>1929: The Inside Story of the Greatest C=
rash in Wall Street History</em>, I was eager to chat about the project and=
 how it came together. I first caught wind of the book back in December 202=
3, but Andrew wasn=E2=80=99t ready to spill the beans. At that point
it was still an amorphous work in progress, and he=E2=80=99s too much of a =
pro to discuss a project prematurely.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Like many o=
f us, Andrew had a vague sense of what occurred during the 1929 crash. He=
=E2=80=99d read the classics=E2=80=94among them, <strong>John Kenneth Galbr=
aith</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>The Great Crash</em> and <strong>John Brooks</s=
trong>=E2=80=99 <em>Once in Golconda</em>. But on a vacation seven or eight=
 years ago, he
decided to get more serious, downloading a bunch of books on the subject. M=
ost of them, he said, had an =E2=80=9Carmchair=E2=80=9D quality: they were =
distant, a tad dry, lacking a crisp, flowing narrative or any feeling that =
the reader was present while events were unfolding. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=
=99t feel like I had read a true character-driven, narrative ticktock, in-t=
he-room, fly-on-the-wall kind of thing,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CI was=
 a little surprised. I thought, <em>Maybe someone has written it</em>. But =
wouldn=E2=80=99t it be really fun
to try to figure out if I could do that?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Andrew s=
et out to see if he could re-create that inside-the-room feel for the incre=
dible events of 1929. Unlike the 2008 financial crisis, which was playing o=
ut before his eyes in real time, the major players from the Depression were=
 long dead. (This comes with its perks, too, as any author knows=E2=80=A6) =
There were plenty of academics to talk to, of course, but he was looking fo=
r
the original source material of the people involved=E2=80=94letters, diary =
entries, memoirs=E2=80=94the stuff tucked away in obscure archives across t=
he country. At times, he doubted if he could find what he needed=E2=80=94th=
e normal authorial anxiety. Unsure of whether he could produce the narrativ=
e he wanted, he didn=E2=80=99t even initially sell the book to his publishe=
r. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t know whether I=E2=80=99d be able to get the so=
rt of granular detail that I was looking for,=E2=80=9D he told me.</p></div=
>
