<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Given everything else he was doing, the work on=
 <em>1929</em> was
intermittent at best. Every time he sat down to write, he=E2=80=99d need at=
 least an hour of uninterrupted time to figure out what he had been thinkin=
g when he last worked on it. =E2=80=9CMy brain was on everything else,=E2=
=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d be on DealBook all day, or on CNBC stu=
ff, or <em>New York Times</em> craziness, or 100 other things.=E2=80=9D The=
re were plenty of stops and starts and dead ends. He=E2=80=99d have thought=
 he=E2=80=99d figured out a scene, or the way the events unfolded, only to =
discover there was no more thread.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But things really st=
arted coming together in the last year or so. =E2=80=9CNot only did the pie=
ces start to fit, but I started finding some new pieces,=E2=80=9D he said. =
Eventually, there was an epiphany. =E2=80=9CThere was a moment where I look=
ed at all the pieces on the table, and I could see how they all connected t=
he way I had hoped.=E2=80=9D Andrew told me his experience working on <em>B=
illions</em> ended up being helpful =E2=80=9Cin terms of
trying to think about the character, and trying to be able to put myself in=
 their shoes. If they had come from [a certain] meeting, what would they ha=
ve been doing next? Who would they have called next?=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">As Andrew navigated his research, he was struck by the parallels b=
etween events from a century ago and the present day, particularly how the =
relationship between the Gilded Age elites and the federal
government foreshadowed the power of today=E2=80=99s billionaire class. But=
 there were other similarities as well. =E2=80=9CThey had many of the same =
issues,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CWe are talking about tariffs today. Well=
, tariffs were an issue then=E2=80=94Smoot Hawley,=E2=80=9D the tariff act =
of 1930. He continued: =E2=80=9CHow do you regulate banks or not regulate b=
anks? What should the Federal Reserve be doing? Should they lower rates? Sh=
ould they increase rates? If they increase rates, are they going to put the=
 economy into a recession, and
there are people fighting on all these different sides. It=E2=80=99s all th=
e same stuff.=E2=80=9D The Great Crash was not just a story about Wall Stre=
et, he concluded, but rather=E2=80=94as with the Great Recession=E2=80=94it=
 was a story about the intersection of Wall Street and Washington.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">The book is currently being edited and fact-checked. Andrew is =
working on the dreaded endnotes, providing the citations for the source mat=
erial he
dug up over the years. Who knows, but it feels like to me <em>1929</em> is =
destined to be a bestseller and a major motion picture. And given all the w=
ays events in the book evoke the events unfolding now, it will be nice to b=
e reminded of how a government and its allied oligarchs approached tough qu=
estions about tariffs, interest rates, and regulation once upon a time. The=
 question now is: Can we wait until October? We could really use some histo=
rical insights <em>now</em> about what happens
when the rich and powerful start running our government.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Over the years t=
hat he was engrossed in finishing <em>1929</em>, Andrew came to have some f=
avorite characters. One was <strong>Carter Glass</strong>, the U.S. senator=
 from Tennessee for whom the Glass-Steagall Act was later named. =E2=80=9CH=
e was the<strong> Elizabeth Warren</strong> of that time,=E2=80=9D he expla=
ined. =E2=80=9CHe really did play a uniquely central role in all of the thi=
ngs
that happened. He was one of the people who actually was worried about what=
 was going to happen the whole time. And he was right.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></=
div>
